comments.comment: Do you have to Misty Stanley-Jones? Can you instead document how folks can look at the list of metrics and their descriptions? Maybe explain how to connect and read the descriptions attached when you are viewing the metrics via jmx? i.e. start up an instance and connect with jvisualvm and then find the hbase beans and list the 'attributes'?

I don't have a big preference, but I realized there is absolutely no mention in the docs of most of these metrics that I keep coming across. I will explore the right way to do it. Got any source material or pointers for me? I haven't actually got any idea what jvisualvm is but I am sure I can find from a google.

Build hbase. Then do ./bin/start-hbase.sh. Standalone mode. Browse to ui. Hit the 'metrics dump' along the top: e.g. http://localhost:60124/jmx. You'll get a JSON dump like this:

This is just the JMX beans as JSON. Its fine only it is missing the 'descriptions' that say what each metric is. Thinking on it, maybe we should add a metrics dump that includes the description?

To see the descriptions, they are published only to jmx. You can view jmx content by browsing the 'mbeans', the java bean-based 'view's jmx publishes, in lots of tools but in java there are two tools that will let you view the jmx content: jconsole and jvisualvm which is jconsole w/ more stuff in it.

Run this on command line: jvisualvm. When it comes up you'll see list of your java processes. See 'local' set. Click the hbase looking one. Right hand side panel gets filled out w/ fancy stuff w/ tabs along top. See the tab 'MBeans' (for management beans – jmx is java management beans).... You'll see 'Hadoop' mentioned in the lefthand panel now. Navigate down through HBase, a subbean, then to the server beans. See 'attributes'. The 'metadata' has descriptions of each jmx attribute. Not pretty but these descriptions are written into hbase code beside their implementation... which is good.. .the display is bad.

Would be good if could point folks at how to find this stuff and/or maybe we should make it so we list out in UI the descriptions beside metric?

Would it be possible to create a flat table of metric name => description that can be generated and published in the book? I think having an offline reference is quite helpful for folks who don't have a running hbase and who have no experience with (or inkling of) JMX.
